{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is the real CLI+git interaction: rename detection comes from actual git status/diff behavior on a real repository. A mocked diff/parser can miss real cases where git emits rename metadata differently, so Integration is rejected. Behavior text that disqualifies lower levels: \"reads a git repository\" and categorizes real change types in CLI output.","test_description":"Create a temporary real git repo, commit a file, rename it, run the CLI as a subprocess, and assert report shows exactly one rename and no paired add/delete for that path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real binary diff handling depends on git subprocess output and real filesystem content; mocks often sanitize/replace binary behavior and can hide crashes (encoding/decoding, subprocess stdout handling). Integration is rejected because behavior explicitly depends on real binary diffs from repository state.","test_description":"In a temp git repo, add/modify a real binary file (e.g., random bytes), run CLI subprocess over changes, assert process exits successfully and binary file is counted in output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.87,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is tied to real git behavior in an unborn repository (no HEAD), which is a subprocess/OS-level condition. Mocked repository adapters can miss actual git error modes, so Integration is rejected. Disqualifying behavior text: tool \"reads a git repository\" and must handle the real no-commit state.","test_description":"Initialize a new git repo with no commits, run the CLI subprocess, assert zero exit (or expected success code) and an empty structured report on stdout.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The required oracle is the repository’s real history as interpreted by git; correctness depends on end-to-end CLI behavior over actual commits/renames/deletions/modifications. Integration with stub history can pass while diverging from true git semantics, so lower levels are insufficient.","test_description":"Build a temp repo with a known sequence of commits containing adds/deletes/renames/modifies, run CLI subprocess for the target range, and assert category counts exactly match the known ground truth from that real history.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This behavior depends on real git index vs working-tree state transitions, which are OS/filesystem + git process semantics. In-process fakes of staging can hide mismatches in actual git command behavior, so Integration is rejected. Disqualifying text: compares staged vs unstaged behavior of repository analysis.","test_description":"In a temp repo, create equivalent staged and unstaged change scenarios for the same content, run CLI subprocess in each scenario, and as